    "# Export An Image from A website\n",
    "\n",
    "import requests\n",
    "from PIL import Image\n",
    "from io import BytesIO\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "# URL of image from the website \n",
    "url = 'https://whatfix.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/employee-churn.png'\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fetch the image from the web\n",
    "response = requests.get(url)\n",
    "img = Image.open(BytesIO(response.content))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Double the size by adjusting the figure dimensions\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(18, 18))  # Adjust image size\n",
    "plt.imshow(img)\n",
    "plt.axis('off')  # Hide axes \n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Disclaimer: I do not own the rights to this image."
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "gLEEr6peWcF7"
   },
   "source": [
    "### Business Understanding \n",
    "\n",
    "The HR department aims to improve employee satisfaction and reduce turnover, which is costly and disruptive. They have collected employee data but need help analyzing it.\n",
    "\n",
    "My role is to examine this data and build a predictive model to identify employees likely to leave. By uncovering key drivers of attrition, I can provide actionable insights to help retain talent, reduce costs, and improve workforce stability.\n",
    "\n",
    "This analysis is critical for supporting the company’s growth and operational efficiency."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "lnRdR6eacUkK"
   },
   "source": [
    "### The HR dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset contains 15,000 rows and 10 columns for the variables listed below. \n",
    "\n",
    "Variable  |Description |\n",
    "-----|-----|\n",
    "satisfaction_level|Employee-reported job satisfaction level [0&ndash;1]|\n",
    "last_evaluation|Score of employee's last performance review [0&ndash;1]|\n",
    "number_project|Number of projects employee contributes to|\n",
    "average_monthly_hours|Average number of hours employee worked per month|\n",
    "time_spend_company|How long the employee has been with the company (years)\n",
    "Work_accident|Whether or not the employee experienced an accident while at work\n",
    "left|Whether or not the employee left the company\n",
    "promotion_last_5years|Whether or not the employee was promoted in the last 5 years\n",
    "Department|The employee's department\n",
    "salary|The employee's salary (U.S. dollars)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Dfnvw1HZsfbd"
   },
   "source": [

   "source": [
    "# Display all column names\n",
    "print(df0.columns.tolist())\n",
    "\n",
    "# Convert all column names to snake_case\n",
    "df0.columns = df0.columns.str.replace(r'(?<!^)(?=[A-Z])', '_', regex=True).str.lower() \n",
    "## add '_' before uppercase letters (A-Z), except at the start of the string. \n",
    "\n",
    "# Check the result\n",
    "df0.info()"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "ohctgiHyFykI"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Lower Bound=1.5\n",
      "Upper Bound=5.5\n",
      "Number of rows containing outliers for 'tenure': 824\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Determine the number of rows containing outliers in 'tenure'\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calculate the IQR for the 'tenure' column\n",
    "Q1 = df['tenure'].quantile(0.25)\n",
    "Q3 = df['tenure'].quantile(0.75)\n",
    "IQR = Q3 - Q1\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define the lower and upper bounds for outliers\n",
    "lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR\n",
    "upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR\n",
    "\n",
    "# Identify rows with outliers\n",
    "outliers = df[(df['tenure'] < lower_bound) | (df['tenure'] > upper_bound)]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'Lower Bound={lower_bound}')\n",
    "print(f'Upper Bound={upper_bound}')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Count the number of rows containing outliers\n",
    "num_outliers = outliers.shape[0]\n",
    "print(f\"Number of rows containing outliers for 'tenure': {num_outliers}\")\n",
    "\n"
   ]

       "<Figure size 288x216 with 1 Axes>"

     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"

   "source": [
    "# Normalize data: \n",
    "\n",
    "# Replot above graphs by Ratio/ in propotion to each specific group: (normalizing data by percentage of each unique value in each variable)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define columns to analyze\n",
    "columns = ['number_project', 'tenure', 'work_accident','promotion_last_5years','department', 'salary']\n",
    "\n",
    "# Loop through columns to create normalized bar plots\n",
    "for col in columns:\n",
    "    # Normalize the data for percentages (cross-tabulation and normalization)\n",
    "    if df[col].dtype == 'object':  # For categorical variables like 'department' and 'salary'\n",
    "        col_left_percent = pd.crosstab(df[col], df['left'], normalize='index') * 100\n",
    "    else:  # For continuous variables like 'number_project', 'tenure', 'work_accident'\n",
    "        col_left_percent = pd.crosstab(df[col], df['left'], normalize='index') * 100\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Convert to long format for plotting\n",
    "    col_left_melted = col_left_percent.reset_index().melt(id_vars=col, var_name='left', value_name='percentage')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Plot the normalized bar plot for each column\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(4, 3))\n",
    "    sns.barplot(data=col_left_melted, x=col, y='percentage', hue='left', palette='Set2')\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Set plot titles and labels\n",
    "    plt.title(f\"Percentage of Left vs {col}\")\n",
    "    plt.xlabel(f\"{col}\")\n",
    "    plt.ylabel(\"Percentage\")\n",
    "    plt.legend(title=\"Left\", labels=[\"Stayed\", \"Left\"])\n",
    "    plt.xticks(rotation=45)\n",
    "    plt.show()\n"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Output: \n",
    "- Projects: Those with little (<=2) or too many projects (>4) has higher rate of quitting. All with 7 projects quitted.   \n",
    "- Tenure: Tenured == 5 has the HIGHEST rate of quitting\n",
    "- Work accidents: no work accident has higher rate of quitting -- work accident is not a determinant. Drop this var. \n",
    "- Department: rate of quitting appeared similar accross department. -- department has no influence on 'left'. Further investigate before dropping this var. \n",
    "- Salary: Low salart group has higher rate of quitting \n",
    "\n",
    "Next: \n",
    "further investigate if 'Department' has significant effect on 'left'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "['sales' 'accounting' 'hr' 'technical' 'support' 'management' 'IT'\n",
      " 'product_mng' 'marketing' 'RandD']\n",
      "Chi-Square Statistic: 20.857513153795892\n",
      "p-value: 0.01329832963300122\n",
      "There is a significant difference in 'left' among the groups in 'department'.\n",
      "\n",
      "Performing pairwise comparisons with Bonferroni correction:\n",
      "No significant differences found between specific groups.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# List all the group in 'department'\n",
    "print(df['department'].unique()) \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a contingency table for 'department' and 'left'\n",
    "contingency_table = pd.crosstab(df['department'], df['left'])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Perform the Chi-Square Test for Independence\n",
    "chi2_result = stats.chi2_contingency(contingency_table)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Extract results\n",
    "chi2_statistic = chi2_result[0]\n",
    "p_value = chi2_result[1]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print overall Chi-Square test result\n",
    "print(\"Chi-Square Statistic:\", chi2_statistic)\n",
    "print(\"p-value:\", p_value)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Interpret the overall test result\n",
    "alpha = 0.05  # Common significance level\n",
    "if p_value < alpha:\n",
    "    print(\"There is a significant difference in 'left' among the groups in 'department'.\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Perform pairwise comparisons\n",
    "    print(\"\\nPerforming pairwise comparisons with Bonferroni correction:\")\n",
    "    departments = df['department'].unique()\n",
    "    pairs = list(combinations(departments, 2))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    significant_pairs = []\n",
    "    corrected_alpha = alpha / len(pairs)  # Bonferroni correction\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for dep1, dep2 in pairs:\n",
    "        # Create contingency table for the pair\n",
    "        pair_table = pd.crosstab(df[df['department'].isin([dep1, dep2])]['department'], \n",
    "                                 df[df['department'].isin([dep1, dep2])]['left'])\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Perform Chi-Square test for the pair\n",
    "        pair_result = stats.chi2_contingency(pair_table)\n",
    "        pair_p_value = pair_result[1]\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Check if the pair is significantly different\n",
    "        if pair_p_value < corrected_alpha:\n",
    "            significant_pairs.append((dep1, dep2, pair_p_value))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    if significant_pairs:\n",
    "        for dep1, dep2, p_val in significant_pairs:\n",
    "            print(f\"Significant difference between {dep1} and {dep2} (p-value: {p_val:.4f})\")\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        print(\"No significant differences found between specific groups.\")\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(\"There is no significant difference in 'left' among the groups in 'department'.\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Output: \n",
    "- The overall test indicates that there is some difference among groups, but pairwise tests with Bonferroni correction did not detect specific group differences. Bonfeeroni correction has increased stringency.  \n",
    "- I'll nor include 'department' in modeling.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

   "source": [
    "# horizontal box plot comparing average_monthly_hours for employees who stayed (left == 0) versus those who left (left == 1) across different number_project or salary or promotion_last_5years.\n",
    "\n",
    "# List of variables to be plotted on the y-axis\n",
    "y_vars = ['salary', 'number_project', 'promotion_last_5years']\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a figure with subplots (one row, three columns)\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(len(y_vars), 1, figsize=(12, 12))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Loop over the list of variables and create boxplots\n",
    "for i, y_var in enumerate(y_vars):\n",
    "    sns.boxplot(\n",
    "        data=df, \n",
    "        x='average_monthly_hours', \n",
    "        y=y_var, \n",

    "        orient='h', \n",

    "    ax[i].invert_yaxis()  # Invert the y-axis to display the categories from top to bottom\n",
    "    ax[i].set_title(f'Monthly Hours vs {y_var.capitalize()}', fontsize=16)\n",
    "    ax[i].set_xlabel('Average Monthly Hours', fontsize=14)\n",
    "    ax[i].set_ylabel(y_var.capitalize(), fontsize=14)\n",
    "    ax[i].legend(title='Employee Status', labels=['Stayed (0)', 'Left (1)'], fontsize=12)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Adjust layout for better spacing between plots\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show the plot\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x864 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "# List of variables to be plotted on the y-axis\n",
    "y_vars = ['salary', 'number_project', 'promotion_last_5years']\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a figure with subplots (one row, three columns)\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(len(y_vars), 1, figsize=(12, 12))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Loop over the list of variables and create boxplots\n",
    "for i, y_var in enumerate(y_vars):\n",
    "    sns.boxplot(\n",
    "        data=df, \n",
    "        x='satisfaction_level',  # Use 'satisfaction_level' for the x-axis\n",
    "        y=y_var,                 # Use the variable from y_vars list for the y-axis\n",
    "        hue='left',              # Group by employee status (stayed vs left)\n",
    "        orient='h',              # Horizontal orientation\n",
    "        ax=ax[i]                 # Specify the axis to draw on\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    ax[i].invert_yaxis()  # Invert the y-axis to display the categories from top to bottom\n",
    "    ax[i].set_title(f'Satisfaction Level vs {y_var.capitalize()}', fontsize=16)\n",
    "    ax[i].set_xlabel('Satisfaction Level', fontsize=14)\n",
    "    ax[i].set_ylabel(y_var.capitalize(), fontsize=14)\n",

    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show the plot\n",
    "plt.show()\n",

   "source": [
    "Output: No LINEAR relatioship between 'satisfaction level', 'last evaluation', 'average monthly hours' and target variable 'left'. However the distribution between stayed and left is very different and worth investigating. \n",
    "\n",
    "Note 1: The 'satisfaction level' data is typically collected infrequently, often on an annual or biannual basis. As a result, it tends to be outdated and may not accurately reflect an individual's real-time satisfaction at the moment they decide to leave. Given these limitations, this variable should be use with caution. At the end of the report, I'll report the evaluation model with, and without 'satisfaction_level'. \n",
    "\n",
    "Note 2: Similar to the 'satisfaction level' data, the 'last evaluation' data is typically collected infrequently, often on an annual or biannual basis. However, 'last evaluation' is a more comprehensive variable, encompassing various factors such as work quality, productivity, skills, and teamwork, and is informed by both staff and supervisor assessments. Given its broader scope and relevance, this variable will be included in the modeling process \n",
    "\n",
    "Note 3: \"Average monthly hours' can be a very tricky and interesting variable needed caution. Often time staffs who decided to leave would work much less hours just before they leave. It would be interesting to investigate the relationship between average monthly hours and satsfaction, last evalutaion, number of projects, and salary. \n"
   ]

    "    diag_kind='kde',\n",

    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Customize the size of green dots after the plot is created\n",
    "for ax in pairplot.axes.flat:\n",
    "    for path in ax.collections:\n",
    "        facecolor = path.get_facecolor()\n",
    "        # Check if the facecolor corresponds to green (darkgreen)\n",
    "        if (facecolor[:, 1] > facecolor[:, 0]).all():  # Green > Red\n",
    "            path.set_sizes([25])  # Set size to half of default (50 -> 25)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Adjust the overall figure size\n",

    "Insights are stated after each code block with comment of --  output. \n",
    "\n",
    "Here are the collection: \n",
    "\n",
    "1. Employees with fewer than 2 or more than 5 projects tend to have a higher rate of leaving.\n",
    "2. Employees with a tenure of 5 years have the highest rate of leaving.\n",
    "3. Employees who have not experienced a work accident tend to leave at higher rates. This suggests work accidents may not be a significant determinant.\n",
    "4. The leave rate appears similar across departments. Therefore 'department' will not be included in the model.\n",
    "5. Employees with lower salaries tend to leave more often.\n",
    "6. Burnout and Attrition: Employees managing 4+ projects and working longer hours are more likely to quit, suggesting burnout as a key factor in attrition. Proper workload management is crucial to retaining valuable employees.\n",
    "7. Satisfaction Level: Employees who left tend to have lower satisfaction levels, regardless of salary or promotion. This highlights the importance of employee satisfaction in retention.\n",
    "8. High Performers Leaving: Employees managing 4+ projects and receiving high evaluations are more likely to leave, raising concerns about losing high performers.\n"

    "# A. Logistic Regression Model: "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Bf2BU6B1QmTg"
   },
   "source": [
    "**Logistic Regression model assumptions**\n",
    "- Outcome variable is categorical\n",
    "- Observations are independent of each other\n",
    "- No severe multicollinearity among X variables\n",
    "- No extreme outliers\n",
    "- Linear relationship between each X variable and the logit of the outcome variable\n",
    "- Sufficiently large sample size"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

    "# Define independent variables (X) by excluding 'left' column\n",
    "X = df1.drop(columns=['left'])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define your dependent variable (y)\n",
    "y = df1['left']\n",
    "\n",
    "# Split the data into training and testing sets (80% train, 20% test)\n",
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2,stratify=y, random_state=168)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initialize the logistic regression model\n",
    "log_reg = LogisticRegression(max_iter=500)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit the model on the training data\n",
    "log_reg.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Predict on the test set\n",
    "y_pred = log_reg.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Evaluate the model\n",
    "accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)\n",
    "conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)\n",
    "class_report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print the results\n",
    "print(\"Accuracy:\", accuracy)\n",
    "print(\"Confusion Matrix:\\n\", conf_matrix)\n",
    "print(\"Classification Report:\\n\", class_report)"

     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Best parameters found:  {'max_depth': 5, 'min_samples_leaf': 2, 'min_samples_split': 2}\n",
      "Best Score: 0.9683737775458852\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# 5. train and decision tree modeling: \n",
    "\n",
    "# Initialize the DecisionTreeClassifier model\n",
    "tree= DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=168)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Model Tuning for better model's performance: \n",
    "# Define the parameter grid\n",
    "param_grid = {'max_depth': [1,3,5],\n",
    "              'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],\n",
    "              'min_samples_leaf': [2, 4, 6]}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Assign a dictionary of scoring metrics to capture\n",
    "scoring = {'accuracy', 'precision', 'recall', 'f1', 'roc_auc'}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initialize GridSearchCV\n",
    "tree1 = GridSearchCV(tree, param_grid, scoring = scoring, cv=5, refit ='roc_auc')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit GridSearchCV to the training data\n",
    "tree1.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print the best parameters found\n",
    "print(\"Best parameters found: \", tree1.best_params_)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Best score using the default refit metric (roc_auc)\n",
    "best_score = tree1.best_score_\n",
    "print('Best Score:', best_score)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Function to extract all the scores for cv: \n",
    "\n",
    "def make_results(model_name:str, model_object, metric:str):\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    Arguments:\n",
    "        model_name (string): what you want the model to be called in the output table\n",
    "        model_object: a fit GridSearchCV object\n",
    "        metric (string): precision, recall, f1, accuracy, or auc\n",
    "  \n",
    "    Returns a pandas df with the F1, recall, precision, accuracy, and auc scores\n",
    "    for the model with the best mean 'metric' score across all validation folds.  \n",
    "    '''\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Create dictionary that maps input metric to actual metric name in GridSearchCV\n",
    "    metric_dict = {'auc': 'mean_test_roc_auc',\n",
    "                   'precision': 'mean_test_precision',\n",
    "                   'recall': 'mean_test_recall',\n",
    "                   'f1': 'mean_test_f1',\n",
    "                   'accuracy': 'mean_test_accuracy'\n",
    "                  }\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Get all the results from the CV and put them in a df\n",
    "    cv_results = pd.DataFrame(model_object.cv_results_)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Isolate the row of the df with the max(metric) score\n",
    "    best_estimator_results = cv_results.iloc[cv_results[metric_dict[metric]].idxmax(), :]\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Extract Accuracy, precision, recall, and f1 score from that row\n",
    "    auc = best_estimator_results.mean_test_roc_auc\n",
    "    f1 = best_estimator_results.mean_test_f1\n",
    "    recall = best_estimator_results.mean_test_recall\n",
    "    precision = best_estimator_results.mean_test_precision\n",
    "    accuracy = best_estimator_results.mean_test_accuracy\n",
    "  \n",
    "    # Create table of results\n",
    "    table = pd.DataFrame()\n",
    "    table = pd.DataFrame({'model': [model_name],\n",
    "                          'precision': [precision],\n",
    "                          'recall': [recall],\n",
    "                          'F1': [f1],\n",
    "                          'accuracy': [accuracy],\n",
    "                          'auc': [auc]\n",
    "                        })\n",
    "  \n",
    "    return table"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    " # Function to extract all the scores for test: \n",
    "\n",
    "def get_scores(model_name:str, model, X_test_data, y_test_data):\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    Generate a table of test scores.\n",
    "\n",
    "    In: \n",
    "        model_name (string):  How you want your model to be named in the output table\n",
    "        model:                A fit GridSearchCV object\n",
    "        X_test_data:          numpy array of X_test data\n",
    "        y_test_data:          numpy array of y_test data\n",
    "\n",
    "    Out: pandas df of precision, recall, f1, accuracy, and AUC scores for your model\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "\n",
    "    preds = model.best_estimator_.predict(X_test_data)\n",
    "\n",
    "    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test_data, preds)\n",
    "    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test_data, preds)\n",
    "    precision = precision_score(y_test_data, preds)\n",
    "    recall = recall_score(y_test_data, preds)\n",
    "    f1 = f1_score(y_test_data, preds)\n",
    "\n",
    "    table = pd.DataFrame({'model': [model_name],\n",
    "                          'precision': [precision], \n",
    "                          'recall': [recall],\n",
    "                          'f1': [f1],\n",
    "                          'accuracy': [accuracy],\n",
    "                          'AUC': [auc]\n",
    "                         })\n",
    "  \n",
    "    return table"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 38,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
       "<div>\n",
       "<style scoped>\n",
       "    .dataframe tbody tr th:only-of-type {\n",
       "        vertical-align: middle;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n",
       "        vertical-align: top;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe thead th {\n",
       "        text-align: right;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "</style>\n",
       "<table border=\"1\" class=\"dataframe\">\n",
       "  <thead>\n",

    "# Initialize the RandomForestClassifier model\n",
    "rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=168)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Model Tuning for better model performance\n",
    "# Define the parameter grid (adjusting for Random Forest)\n",
    "param_grid = {\n",
    "    'n_estimators': [10,30,50],  # Number of trees in the forest\n",
    "    'max_depth': [1,3, None],  # Maximum depth of the tree\n",
    "    'min_samples_split': [1, 10, 20, 50],  # Minimum number of samples required to split an internal node\n",
    "    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 3],  # Minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node\n",
    "    'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt']  # Number of features to consider for best split\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Assign a dictionary of scoring metrics to capture\n",
    "scoring = {'accuracy', 'precision', 'recall', 'f1', 'roc_auc'}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initialize GridSearchCV\n",
    "rf1 = GridSearchCV(rf, param_grid, scoring=scoring, cv=5, refit='roc_auc')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit GridSearchCV to the training data\n",
    "rf1.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",

   "source": [
    "Before building the model, I hesitated to include \"satisfaction_level\" because I assumed it is collected infrequently and might not reflect real-time satisfaction, potentially misleading decision-making. However, modeling (tree or RF) shows that \"satisfaction_level\" has a strong influence, significantly improving performance metrics like F1. Despite being outdated (I should confirm this with the HR), it can reveal patterns in satisfaction and help identify systemic issues, acting as a proxy for related factors like job satisfaction and workplace dynamics.\n",
    "\n",
    "Below is the evaluation for models WITHOUT 'statisfaction_level': \n",

    "# Plot Feature importances for rf1\n",
    "\n",
    "best_rf1 = rf1.best_estimator_\n",
    "\n",
    "# Access the feature importances from the best estimator\n",
    "rf1_importances = best_rf1.feature_importances_\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a pandas Series for visualization\n",
    "forest_importances = pd.Series(rf1_importances, index=X.columns).sort_values(ascending=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the feature importances horizontally\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 4))  # Adjust figure size for better visibility\n",
    "forest_importances.plot.barh(ax=ax)\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Feature Importances\")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"Importance\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Features\")\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "401PgchTPr4E"
   },
   "source": [
    "## Key Insights and Action Plan:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Stop Burnout, Save Talent: Employees with too many or too few projects are quitting. Limit project loads and reward long hours—or don’t require them at all.\n",
    "2. Fix the 5-Year Itch: Most 5-year employees are leaving. Investigate why and offer promotions or incentives to keep them engaged.\n",
    "3. Pay and Stay: Low pay and low satisfaction drive attrition. Boost morale with fair compensation and recognition.\n",
    "4. Keep High Performers Happy: Top employees juggling too much are leaving. Recognize contributions fairly and avoid overloading them.\n",
    "5. Clear Policies, Happy Teams: Confusion about overtime and workload fuels frustration. Communicate policies and expectations clearly.\n",
    "6. Culture Counts: Turnover is steady across departments. Start honest conversations to improve company culture and retain employees."
   ]
  }
